# pi-minions

Minimal recursive subagent orchestration for pi. No bundled agents, no opinions.

## Quick Start

**Install from GitHub:**

```bash
pi install https://github.com/kalindudc/pi-minions
```

**Or install locally for development:**

```bash
git clone https://github.com/kalindudc/pi-minions.git
pi install ./pi-minions
```

Spawn a minion:
```bash
# Foreground (blocks parent until complete)
/spawn Research the latest TypeScript 5.7 features

# Background (returns immediately, queues result)
/spawn --bg Refactor the auth module for better testability
```

## Features

- **In-process sessions** - no child processes, streaming progress, clean abort
- **Foreground & background modes** - block parent or fire-and-forget
- **Live detach** - send running minions to background without interruption
- **Steering** - inject messages into running minions mid-execution
- **Agent discovery** - use named agents from `~/.pi/agent/agents/` or ephemeral minions
- **Result queue** - auto-delivery of background results to parent LLM
- **Hierarchical tracking** - tree structure for nested spawning
- **Transcript logging** - full conversation logs per minion

## Core Concepts

### Minions

A minion is an isolated pi agent session running in-process. It has:
- Own conversation context (separate from parent)
- Built-in tools only (read, bash, edit, write, grep, find, ls)
- No extensions (prevents recursive spawning)
- Fail-fast system prompt (STOP on failure, no fabrication)

### Foreground vs Background

| Mode | Use When | Parent Behavior | Result Delivery |
|------|----------|-----------------|-----------------|
| **Foreground** | Need result immediately | Blocks until complete | Tool call result in conversation |
| **Background** | Long-running, parallel work | Returns immediately | Auto-delivered to LLM when done |

### Named vs Ephemeral Agents

```bash
# Ephemeral (default) - uses built-in minion template
/spawn Analyze the error logs

# Named - uses custom agent from disk
/spawn --agent scout Find all TODO comments in src/
```

Agents are discovered from:
- `~/.pi/agent/agents/`
- `.pi/agents/`

## Commands & Tools

### Commands (User-Initiated)

| Command | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `/spawn [--bg] [--agent NAME] [--model MODEL] <task>` | Spawn a minion |
| `/minions` or `/minions list` | Show running minions and pending results |
| `/minions show <id\|name>` | Detailed view of a minion |
| `/minions bg <id\|name>` | Send running minion to background |
| `/minions steer <id\|name> <message>` | Inject message into running minion |

### Tools (LLM-Callable)

| Tool | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `spawn` | Delegate task to foreground minion |
| `spawn_bg` | Delegate task to background minion |
| `halt` | Abort running minion(s) by ID/name |
| `list_agents` | Discover available named agents |
| `list_minions` | List running minions and pending results |
| `show_minion` | Get detailed minion status |
| `steer_minion` | Send steering message to running minion |

See [docs/reference.md](docs/reference.md) for detailed API documentation.

## Common Patterns

### Parallel Research
```bash
/spawn --bg Research React 19 server components
/spawn --bg Research Next.js 15 migration guide
/spawn --bg Research Vercel deployment best practices
# All three run in parallel, results auto-delivered
```

### Sequential Work with Detach
```bash
/spawn Analyze the codebase and create refactoring plan
# Later, while planning is running...
/minions bg planning-minion
# Parent unlocks, minion continues, result queued
```

### Steering Running Minions
```bash
/spawn --bg Run full test suite and analyze failures
# Later, adjust scope mid-run...
/minions steer test-runner "Focus only on integration tests"
```

See [docs/patterns.md](docs/patterns.md) for more usage patterns and workflows.

## Environment Variables

| Variable | Description | Default |
|----------|-------------|---------|
| `PI_MINIONS_DEBUG` | Enable debug logging to `tmp/logs/debug.log` | `0` |

## Logging

- **Debug log**: `tmp/logs/debug.log` (when `PI_MINIONS_DEBUG=1`)
- **Transcripts**: `tmp/logs/minions/<id>-<name>.log` (per-minion conversation)

## Development

```bash
# Install dependencies
npm install

# Run tests
npm test

# Type check
npm run typecheck

# Watch tests
npm run test:watch
```

### Creating a Release

This project uses git-based releases with semantic versioning and a two-step process:

**Step 1: Prepare release (in pi)**
```bash
/prompt release
```
This analyzes commits, generates CHANGELOG, and updates files.

**Step 2: Finalize release (in terminal)**
```bash
./scripts/release.sh
```
This reads the version from package.json, creates the commit, tag, and pushes to GitHub.

The workflow:
1. Analyzes commits since last tag
2. Parses conventional commit messages (`feat:`, `fix:`, etc.)
3. Auto-determines version bump (major/minor/patch)
4. Generates CHANGELOG entry
5. Updates `package.json` and `CHANGELOG.md`
6. Shows diff for your review
7. You run the script to finalize

### Conventional Commits

This project uses [conventional commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) for releases:

- `feat:` - New features (minor version bump)
- `fix:` - Bug fixes (patch version bump)  
- `docs:` - Documentation changes (patch version bump)
- `chore:` - Maintenance tasks (patch version bump)
- `test:` - Test updates (patch version bump)
- `BREAKING CHANGE:` or `!` - Breaking changes (major version bump)

Examples:
```bash
# Single change
git commit -m "feat: add session resume support"

# Multiple changes in one commit
git commit -m "feat: add live detach support

Also fixes minion name persistence bug and updates documentation."

# Breaking change
git commit -m "feat!: change spawn API

BREAKING CHANGE: spawn now returns status instead of exitCode"
```

**Note:** A single commit can include multiple types of changes. The release workflow will parse commit bodies to extract all changes.

### Updating Documentation

Review and update documentation after implementation changes:

```bash
# In pi session
/prompt update-docs
```

This audits all docs against current implementation and proposes updates.

